\f0\fs28 This paper contributes to the literature in several ways. First, to the best of my knowledge, I am the first to document empirical evidence that suggests women may be held to higher standards in the peer review process (as opposed to its outcome). Higher standards have recently been established using citations as a proxy for manuscript quality{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://767535AE-6FB7-41E7-8E43-34579715C781"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\fs28 [#Card2020,Moon2020,Grossbard2018]
\f2\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28 .}} They also align with research on employee performance reviews, teaching evaluations and online comments: women receive more abusive feedback, less credit for intelligence and creativity and are expected to be more organised, prepared and clear
\f2\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\fs28 [see, *e.g.*,\\]\\[][#Boring2017,Mengel2017,Correll2016,Gardiner2016,Wu2019]
\f2\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28 .\
Second, this paper proposes a novel explanation for academia's "Publishing Paradox", "Leaky Pipe\\\\-line" and general promotion gap. Higher standards cause collateral damage to women's productivity: spending more time revising old research means there\'92s less time for new research; fewer papers results in fewer promotions, possibly driving women into fairer {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://734054EA-3324-4781-B682-18F902A1D479"}}{\fldrslt fields.}} They may also help explain why so few women publish entirely female-authored papers, despite being the work tenure committees give them the most credit for
\f2\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\fs28 [#Sarsons2020]
\f2\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28 .\
Third, my conclusions relate to a more general debate about gender differences in labour market {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://0F408CF3-FA3A-424E-A023-B4A443D8B373"}}{\fldrslt outcomes.}} Higher standards impose a quantity vs. quality trade-off that characterises female output in many professions---*
\f1\i e.g.
\f0\i0 *, doctors, real estate agents and airline pilots 
\f2\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\fs28 [for a discussion, see\\]\\[][#Hengel2017]
\f2\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28 . Their downstream effects may contribute to several employment phenomena, including women's tendencies to concentrate in certain sectors and occupations
\f2\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\fs28 [#Blau2016,Cortes2016]
\f2\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28 , under-negotiate pay
\f2\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\fs28 [#Babcock2003]
\f2\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28  and apply only to jobs they feel fully qualified for
\f2\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\fs28 [#Mohr2014]
\f2\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28 . They may also reinforce work habits---*
\f1\i e.g.
\f0\i0 *, conscientiousness, tenacity and diligence---that correlate with quality and connote "femininity": for example, female physicians consult longer with patients
\f2\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\fs28 [#Roter2004]
\f2\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28 , female politicians fundraise more intensely
\f2\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\fs28 [#Jenkins2007]
\f2\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28 , female faculty commit fewer instances of academic misconduct
\f2\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\fs28 [#Fang2013]
\f2\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28  and female lawyers make fewer ethical violations
